revision.text:
The '''Cartmel Masterplan''' is a fan name for the planned ''[[Doctor Who]]'' [[backstory]] developed primarily by [[Andrew Cartmel]], [[Ben Aaronovitch]] and [[Marc Platt (writer)|Marc Platt]], by which they intended to restore some of the mystery of [[The Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor's]] background that had been lost through revelation of the existing backstory.<ref name="scriptdoctor">{{cite book |title=Script Doctor: The Inside Story of ''Doctor Who'' 1986–89 |last=Cartmel |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Cartmel |year=2005 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn |location=London |isbn=1-903111-89-7 |pages=134–135}}</ref> Although hints were dropped in the last two seasons, the proposed revelations never materialised on screen as the programme was not renewed for another season in 1990.

Some of the stories during the [[Seventh Doctor]]'s tenure were intended to deal with the lack of mystery by suggesting that much of what was believed about the Doctor was wrong and that he was a far more powerful and mysterious figure than previously thought. In an untelevised scene in ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (1988), the Doctor stated that he was "far more than just another [[Time Lord]]." In ''[[Silver Nemesis]]'' (1988), lines about the creation of [[List of Doctor Who items#Validium|validium]] and Lady Peinforte knowing the Doctor's secrets were meant to point towards this mystery.<ref name="scriptdoctor" />

The suspension of the series in 1989 meant that none of these hints were ever resolved,<ref>{{cite book |last=Howe |first=David J |author-link=David J. Howe |last2=Walker |first2=Stephen James |author-link2=Stephen James Walker |last3=Stammers |first3=Mark |date=2005 |title=The Handbook: The Unofficial and Unauthorised Guide to the Production of Doctor Who |url= |location= |publisher=[[Telos Publishing]] |page=726 |isbn=1903889596 }}</ref> and the subsequent production teams after [[History of Doctor Who#2000s|the TV series resumed airing in 2005]] did not directly pick up on these hints either. Despite this, 2010s [[executive producer]] [[Steven Moffat]] acknowledged in ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' that the 1989 season "isn't so different" to the "new show" [[Russell T Davies]] and he made after 2005, and felt it was "extraordinary" how close [[Rona Munro]]'s ''[[Survival (Doctor Who)|Survival]]'' (1989) was if you put it next to Davies' "[[Rose (Doctor Who episode)|Rose]]" (2005),<ref>{{cite journal |last=Moffat |first=Steven |author-link=Steven Moffat |last2= |first2= |date=August 2015 |title=Steven Moffat |url= |journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |location=Tunbridge Wells |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=#488 |pages=4 |doi= }}</ref> while in a 2014 interview with Cartmel in ''Doctor Who Magazine'', Aaronovitch acknowledged that the style of "today"'s ''Doctor Who'' is "like Rona's stuff", and Cartmel felt that the similarities between ''Remembrance'' and "[[The Day of the Doctor]]" (2013) made ''Remembrance'' "perhaps the closest thing in the twentieth-century series to a dry run" for "The Day of the Doctor".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cartmel |first=Andrew |author-link=Andrew Cartmel |last2= |first2= |date=August 2014 |title=The Cartmel Master Plan Part Two: More Than Just a Time Lord |url= |journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |location=Tunbridge Wells |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=#475 |pages=29 |doi= }}</ref> The "Masterplan" was used as a guide for the [[Virgin New Adventures]] series of novels featuring the Seventh Doctor,<ref name="ahistory380">{{cite book |title=AHistory: An Unauthorized History of the ''Doctor Who'' universe |last=Parkin |first=Lance |authorlink=Lance Parkin |author2=Lars Pearson |edition=2nd |year=2007 |publisher=[[Mad Norwegian Press]] |location=Des Moines, Iowa |isbn=978-0-9759446-6-0 |page=380}}</ref> and the revelations about the Doctor's origins were written into the novel ''[[Lungbarrow]]'' (1997) by Marc Platt. These origins were ignored and even contradicted in subsequent on screen stories.

==The Other==
{{multiple issues|section=yes|
{{fiction|section|date=August 2015}}
{{fanpov|section|date=August 2015}}
{{story|section|date=August 2015}}
}}
Cartmel felt that years of explanations about the Doctor's origins and the [[Time Lord]]s had removed much of the mystery and strength of the character of the Doctor, and decided to make the Doctor "once again more than a mere chump of a Time Lord".<ref name="scriptdoctor" /> To do this, he built on the established mythology of the Time Lords:{{quote|... [[Omega (Doctor Who)|Omega]] and [[Rassilon]] were the founding fathers of [[Gallifrey]]. They towered above the Time Lords who followed. They were demigods. [Dialogue in ''Silver Nemesis'' was] a subtle attempt to say that there was a third presence there in the shadowy days of Gallifrey's creation. In other words, the Doctor was also there. So he's more than a Time Lord. He's one of these half-glimpsed demigods.<ref name="scriptdoctor" />}}
More of these hints would have been seen in the story ''Lungbarrow'', which was at one point planned for the programme's 1988–89 series. ''Lungbarrow'' would have been set in the Doctor's ancestral home on Gallifrey, but the story was abandoned; elements were adapted into the broadcast story ''[[Ghost Light (Doctor Who)|Ghost Light]]'' (1989), but none of the Time Lord backstory survived the transformation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Script Doctor: The Inside Story of ''Doctor Who'' 1986–89 |last=Cartmel |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Cartmel |year=2005 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn |location=London |isbn=1-903111-89-7 |pages=171–172}}</ref> However, author [[Marc Platt (writer)|Marc Platt]] eventually adapted his ideas for ''Lungbarrow'' (along with other elements of the "Masterplan"){{vague|date=August 2015}}{{clarify|date=August 2015}} into a ''Doctor Who'' [[Lungbarrow|novel]] for the [[Virgin New Adventures]] series.

In 2014, Cartmel speculated that the "great secret" Lady Peinforte knew about the Doctor in ''Silver Nemesis'' was "perhaps" connected to his name, which during the siege on the Fields of Trenzalore in "[[The Time of the Doctor]]" (2013) is said to be what would allow the Time Lords to return to the universe.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cartmel |first=Andrew |author-link=Andrew Cartmel |last2= |first2= |date=August 2014 |location=Tunbridge Wells |title=The Cartmel Master Plan Part Two: More Than Just a Time Lord |url= |journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=#475 |pages=33 |doi= }}</ref>

The [[Other (Doctor Who)|Other]] was first mentioned explicitly in the novelisation of ''Remembrance of the Daleks'' (1990) by Ben Aaronovitch as a shadowy figure in Time Lord history, one of the founding Triumvirate of Time Lord society after the overthrow of the cult of the Pythia that had, until then, dominated [[Gallifrey]].<ref name="ahistory380" /> The other two members of the Triumvirate were [[Rassilon]] and [[Omega (Doctor Who)|Omega]].

Of the three, the Other's origins are the most obscure, with the circumstances of his birth and appearance being a mystery. Like Rassilon, various contradictory legends surround the Other, some hinting that he had powers surpassing that of Rassilon or Omega, and some even suggesting that he was not born on the Time Lords' home world of [[Gallifrey]]. Even his name is lost to time, which is why he is simply referred to as "the Other". A minor Gallifreyan festival known as Otherstide is celebrated yearly in his honour.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}

==Susan Foreman==
[[Retroactive continuity|Retconning]] the Doctor's backstory was complicated by the existence of [[Susan Foreman]], who was presented in the television series' earliest days as the Doctor's granddaughter.<ref>{{cite serial |title=An Unearthly Child |title-link=An Unearthly Child |episode=An Unearthly Child |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Anthony (writer) |last=Coburn |author-link=Anthony Coburn |first2=Waris (director) |last2=Hussein |author-link2=Waris Hussein |network=[[BBC]] |station= |city= |date=23 November 1963 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Barbara:''' And this is your grandfather? '''Susan:''' Yes. '''Barbara:''' Well, why didn't you tell us that? '''First Doctor:''' I don't discuss my private life with strangers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=The Daleks |title-link=The Daleks |episode=The Rescue |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Terry (writer) |last=Nation |author-link=Terry Nation |first2=Richard (director) |last2=Martin |author-link2=Richard Martin (television director) |credits= |network=[[BBC]] |station= |city= |date=1 February 1964 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Alydon:''' Well, then stay and advise us, please. '''First Doctor:''' No, no, thank you. We're much too far away from home, my granddaughter and I. Thank you all the same. It's a nice gesture on your part.}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=The Edge of Destruction |title-link=The Edge of Destruction |episode=The Brink of Disaster |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=David (writer) |last=Whitaker |author-link=David Whitaker (screenwriter) |first2=Frank (director) |last2=Cox |author-link2=Frank Cox (director) |credits= |network=[[BBC]] |station= |city= |date=15 February 1964 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''First Doctor:''' You know, my dear child, I think your old grandfather is going a tiny little bit around the bend.}}</ref> In different versions of the "Masterplan", different explanations were presented to deal with this: according to writer [[Lance Parkin]], in the "original" version of the Masterplan, the Doctor rescued Susan as an infant from Gallifrey's recent past.<ref name="ahistorysusan">{{cite book |title=AHistory: An Unauthorized History of the ''Doctor Who'' universe |last=Parkin |first=Lance |authorlink=Lance Parkin |author2=Lars Pearson |year=2007 |edition=2nd |publisher=[[Mad Norwegian Press]] |location=Des Moines, Iowa |isbn=978-0-9759446-6-0 |pages=396–398}}</ref>

According to the novel of ''Lungbarrow'', [[Susan Foreman]] was the granddaughter of "[[Other (Doctor Who)|the Other]]", who may have been reincarnated as the Doctor. The Doctor, in his [[First Doctor|first incarnation]], travelled back to the dawn of Time Lord civilisation and rescued a teenaged Susan, who recognised him as her grandfather. The Doctor did not initially recognise her, but knew that this was somehow true.<ref name="ahistorysusan"/> This version of Susan's origins is reflected in many ''Doctor Who'' spin-offs,{{vague|date=August 2015}}{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} but not in the TV series under head writer and [[executive producer]] [[Steven Moffat]]. In "[[The Rings of Akhaten]]" (2013), the [[Eleventh Doctor]] mentions that he travelled to the rings of the planet Akhaten "a long time ago with my granddaughter",<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Rings of Akhaten |episode-link=The Rings of Akhaten |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Neil (writer) |last=Cross |author-link=Neil Cross |first2=Farren (director) |last2=Blackburn |author-link2=Farren Blackburn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=6 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=7 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> while in "[[Death in Heaven]]" (2014), written by Moffat, the [[Twelfth Doctor]]'s companion [[Clara Oswald]] refers to the Doctor's missing "children and grandchildren".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episode-link=Death in Heaven |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Moffat, answering a question in ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' regarding the Doctor's marriages, referred to "some highly inventive material in the Virgin ''New Adventures'' books" that contradicts the ''Doctor Who'' TV series, but thinks this is a "separate (and equally valid) continuity" to the TV series. He also acknowledges that the Doctor "didn't just have children, he had ''grandchildren''", and that "Actually, he had the beginnings of a dynasty."<ref>{{cite journal |last=Moffat |first=Steven |author-link=Steven Moffat |last2= |first2= |date=February 2015 |title=Steven Moffat |url= |journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |location=Tunbridge Wells |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=#482 |pages=4 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>

