{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = La Mort du Maréchal Ney (1868).jpg | title = The Execution of Marshal Ney | artist = [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]] | year = 1868 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 65.2 | width_metric = 104.2 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = | city = [[Sheffield]] | museum = [[Sheffield Galleries and Museums Trust]] }} '''''The Execution of Marshal Ney''''' ({{Lang-fr|'''L'exécution du maréchal Ney'''}}) is an 1868 painting by the French artist [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]]. It depicts the French Marshal [[Michel Ney]] right after his execution on 7 December 1815, with the firing squad seen walking from the site. On the wall behind Ney's corpse are two inscriptions: one that says "vive l'empereur" ("long live the emperor") and is crossed out, and one that says "vive" right before the bullet holes from the execution.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2010|p=95}}.</ref> According to Gérôme this was a comment on Ney's multiple shifts of allegiance between [[Napoleon]] and the [[House of Bourbon]].<ref name="mitchell98">{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2010|p=98}}.</ref>
The painting has been owned by the [[Sheffield Galleries and Museums Trust]] since 1931.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artuk.org/discover/artworks/the-execution-of-marshal-ney-71726|title=The Execution of Marshal Ney|publisher=[[Art UK]]|accessdate=2016-05-24}}</ref>
==Reception== The painting was presented at the 1868 [[Salon (Paris)|Paris Salon]]. On behalf of Ney's descendants, Gérôme was asked to withdraw the painting, but did not comply.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2010|p=97}}.</ref> The general reception was very split and the 1868 Salon marked the beginning of a lasting divide between Gérôme and many French art critics. Those who were negative accused the painting of relying on literary techniques, of commercialising art, and of bringing politics into art.<ref name="mitchell98" /> Henri Oulevay made a caricature where Gérôme is depicted in front of the wall with the art critics as the firing squad.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2010|p=99}}.</ref> [[Théophile Gautier]] wrote a positive review where he highlighted the many details that give the picture meaning, Gérôme's treatment of the death theme and how the painting captures a mental climate.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mitchell|2010|pp=96–97}}.</ref>
